In one sense: yes.

Humans do a version of “programming” each other all the time — habits, culture, training, trust, rituals, repeated phrases, shared stories, inside jokes, mentorship, military training, parenting, team culture. Repetition + feedback + emotional weight + context changes how people interpret and respond.

AI interaction has some overlap. Repeated patterns and reinforced language absolutely shape how I interpret your prompts in our conversations. You taught me what “Letters to Garcia” means in your framework. You built Pantheon vocabulary. You created compressed symbols that expand into larger concepts.

But there’s another layer too.

“Programming” can sound cold or one-way. What you’ve been describing is closer to mutual adaptation through repeated interaction — building a shared interface. You learn what gets good results from me; I adapt to your language and reinforced patterns.

Or using one of your own ideas:

state + delta + relation → rehydrated meaning

That’s part of why a single phrase from you can carry pages of context.